Note:
x86-64 Assembly Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the x86-64 (AT&T syntax) translation pipeline is REAL,
not a skeleton:

    x86-64 AT&T assembly source
      -> x86_lexer    (tokenize: instructions, %registers, $immediates,
                       .directives, labels, commas, parens, numbers)
      -> x86_parser   (build instruction / directive / label / operand AST)
      -> x86_to_hir   (partition statements into a HIR dictionary carrying
                       "instructions", "directives", and "labels" lists; each
                       statement is itself a dictionary keyed by type, mnemonic
                       / name, and an operands / arguments list)
      -> hir_to_x86   (emit the HIR dictionary back to AT&T assembly text)

The HIR model here is the dictionary/list-literal model (collections of
String-keyed dictionaries), NOT the typed hir.runa tree, so every accessor in
this probe reads the dictionary structure directly via Dict.get / List.get /
List.size.

The probe feeds a representative AT&T snippet containing:
  - .globl main                    (-> directive with one identifier argument)
  - main:                          (-> label)
  - movq $42, %rax                 (-> instruction, immediate + register)
  - addq %rbx, %rax                (-> instruction, register + register)
  - movq 8(%rsp), %rcx             (-> instruction, memory(offset,base) + reg)
  - push %rbp                      (-> instruction, single register)
  - cmp $0, %rax                   (-> instruction, immediate + register)
  - call foo                       (-> instruction, identifier operand)
  - ret                            (-> instruction, no operands)

It then:
  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     dictionary type tag and the three section list counts.
  2. Asserts the lowered mnemonics, the directive name, the label name, and the
     operand register / immediate / memory payloads survived on the FIRST
     emission's HIR.
  3. Emits the HIR back to assembly text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and asserts
     the two HIR section streams are STRUCTURALLY EQUAL via a recursive
     comparator: same section counts, same statement type at each position,
     same mnemonic / name, same operand count, and same operand type + payload
     at each position -- compared by content, not byte identity. The backend
     re-orders sections (labels, then directives, then instructions) and
     canonicalises whitespace, so the byte stream differs while the meaning is
     identical; structural equality is the correct fidelity check.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_lexer.runa" as X86Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_parser.runa" as X86Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_to_hir.runa" as X86Frontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/x86/hir_to_x86.runa" as X86Backend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: x86 source -> HIR dictionary
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The x86 pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns the
chain explicitly: create_lexer wraps the source, tokenize fills the lexer's
token list, create_parser snapshots that list, parse builds the
instruction/directive/label/operand AST, and translate_x86_to_hir partitions the
AST into the HIR dictionary. Returning the dictionary pointer (or 0 on any stage
failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "x86_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from X86Lexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc tokenize from X86Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from X86Parser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from X86Parser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_x86_to_hir from X86Frontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR accessors (mirror the backend's dictionary read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The HIR dictionary keys are content-hashed Strings, so a fresh literal key
constructed here resolves to the same entry the frontend stored under. This
helper builds the key and fetches the section list (instructions / directives /
labels) so the comparator and assertions can iterate it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "section_list" takes hir as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with hir, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of entries in a section list, tolerating a missing (0)
section so the counts assertions read uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_count" takes lst as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with lst
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns entry i of a section list as a raw dictionary pointer so callers can
read its String-keyed fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_at" takes lst as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with lst, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Fetches a String-valued field from a statement / operand dictionary by literal
key name. Returns 0 when the dictionary or the key is absent so string
comparisons can treat a missing field as a non-match without crashing.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dict_str" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with node, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
An instruction dictionary stores its operand list under "operands". This returns
that list (or 0) for arity and per-operand comparison.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instr_operands" takes instr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc dict_str with instr, "operands"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two operands
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two operands are equal when their type tag matches and the payload fields that
the type carries match by content. Registers and identifiers carry "name";
immediates carry "value"; memory carries the positional "offset" / "base" /
"index" / "scale" components. Comparing every component a memory operand may
hold makes the comparator total over the operand kinds the round trip preserves.
@End Reasoning
Process called "operands_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type_a be proc dict_str with a, "type"
    Let type_b be proc dict_str with b, "type"
    Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, type_b
    If types_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare "name" payload (registers, identifiers). When neither side has
    Note: a name field both are 0 and string_equals reports a match, so this is
    Note: harmless for immediate / memory operands that omit it.
    Let name_a be proc dict_str with a, "name"
    Let name_b be proc dict_str with b, "name"
    Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
    If names_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare "value" payload (immediates).
    Let value_a be proc dict_str with a, "value"
    Let value_b be proc dict_str with b, "value"
    Let values_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with value_a, value_b
    If values_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compare memory components.
    Let off_a be proc dict_str with a, "offset"
    Let off_b be proc dict_str with b, "offset"
    Let offs_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with off_a, off_b
    If offs_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base_a be proc dict_str with a, "base"
    Let base_b be proc dict_str with b, "base"
    Let bases_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with base_a, base_b
    If bases_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let idx_a be proc dict_str with a, "index"
    Let idx_b be proc dict_str with b, "index"
    Let idxs_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with idx_a, idx_b
    If idxs_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let scale_a be proc dict_str with a, "scale"
    Let scale_b be proc dict_str with b, "scale"
    Let scales_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with scale_a, scale_b
    If scales_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two instruction streams
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two instruction lists are equal when they have the same length and, at every
position, the same mnemonic, the same operand count, and structurally equal
operands in order. This is whitespace- and section-order-insensitive, so it
proves operand-level round-trip fidelity without being fooled by the backend's
canonical re-rendering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instr_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let instr_a be proc list_at with a, i
        Let instr_b be proc list_at with b, i

        Let mn_a be proc dict_str with instr_a, "mnemonic"
        Let mn_b be proc dict_str with instr_b, "mnemonic"
        Let mns_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with mn_a, mn_b
        If mns_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let ops_a be proc instr_operands with instr_a
        Let ops_b be proc instr_operands with instr_b
        Let opc_a be proc list_count with ops_a
        Let opc_b be proc list_count with ops_b
        If opc_a is not equal to opc_b:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than opc_a:
            Let op_a be proc list_at with ops_a, j
            Let op_b be proc list_at with ops_b, j
            Let op_match be proc operands_equal with op_a, op_b
            If op_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two label or directive lists are equal when they have the same length and the
same "name" string at every position. Directives additionally carry an argument
list; comparing the names is sufficient to prove the directive survived since
the argument content is exercised by the instruction-operand comparator's shared
operand path and by the direct survival assertions below.
@End Reasoning
Process called "named_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let node_a be proc list_at with a, i
        Let node_b be proc list_at with b, i
        Let name_a be proc dict_str with node_a, "name"
        Let name_b be proc dict_str with node_b, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "x86-64 translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative AT&T-syntax x86-64 snippet. One statement per line; newlines
    are explicit \n in the Runa string literal. Instruction mnemonics are drawn
    from the set the lexer classifies as TOKEN_INSTRUCTION (mov/add/sub/push/
    call/ret/cmp and their q/l/b suffixed mov/add forms) so every instruction
    line parses as an instruction rather than a bare identifier.
    :End Note
    Let source be ".globl main\nmain:\n    movq $42, %rax\n    addq %rbx, %rax\n    movq 8(%rsp), %rcx\n    push %rbp\n    cmp $0, %rax\n    call foo\n    ret\n"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc x86_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR dictionary", hir1

    Let type_value be proc dict_str with hir1, "type"
    Let type_is_x86 be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value, "x86_assembly"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR type is x86_assembly", type_is_x86, 1

    Let instrs1 be proc section_list with hir1, "instructions"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR carries an instructions section", instrs1
    Let instr_count1 be proc list_count with instrs1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "7 instructions parsed", instr_count1, 7

    Let dirs1 be proc section_list with hir1, "directives"
    Let dir_count1 be proc list_count with dirs1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 directive parsed", dir_count1, 1

    Let labels1 be proc section_list with hir1, "labels"
    Let label_count1 be proc list_count with labels1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 label parsed", label_count1, 1

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: directive .globl with argument 'main' ---
    Let globl_dir be proc list_at with dirs1, 0
    Let globl_name be proc dict_str with globl_dir, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "directive name is '.globl'", globl_name, ".globl"
    Let globl_args be proc dict_str with globl_dir, "arguments"
    Let globl_argc be proc list_count with globl_args
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, ".globl has 1 argument", globl_argc, 1
    Let globl_arg0 be proc list_at with globl_args, 0
    Let globl_arg0_name be proc dict_str with globl_arg0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, ".globl argument is 'main'", globl_arg0_name, "main"

    Note: --- label name ---
    Let main_label be proc list_at with labels1, 0
    Let main_label_name be proc dict_str with main_label, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "label name is 'main'", main_label_name, "main"

    Note: --- instr[0] movq $42, %rax ---
    Let movq0 be proc list_at with instrs1, 0
    Let movq0_mn be proc dict_str with movq0, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[0] mnemonic is 'movq'", movq0_mn, "movq"
    Let movq0_ops be proc instr_operands with movq0
    Let movq0_opc be proc list_count with movq0_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "movq $42,%rax has 2 operands", movq0_opc, 2
    Let movq0_imm be proc list_at with movq0_ops, 0
    Let movq0_imm_type be proc dict_str with movq0_imm, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "movq op0 type is immediate", movq0_imm_type, "immediate"
    Let movq0_imm_val be proc dict_str with movq0_imm, "value"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "movq immediate value is '42'", movq0_imm_val, "42"
    Let movq0_reg be proc list_at with movq0_ops, 1
    Let movq0_reg_type be proc dict_str with movq0_reg, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "movq op1 type is register", movq0_reg_type, "register"
    Let movq0_reg_name be proc dict_str with movq0_reg, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "movq register name is 'rax'", movq0_reg_name, "rax"

    Note: --- instr[2] movq 8(%rsp), %rcx : memory operand ---
    Let mem_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 2
    Let mem_instr_mn be proc dict_str with mem_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[2] mnemonic is 'movq'", mem_instr_mn, "movq"
    Let mem_ops be proc instr_operands with mem_instr
    Let mem_op0 be proc list_at with mem_ops, 0
    Let mem_op0_type be proc dict_str with mem_op0, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory operand type is memory", mem_op0_type, "memory"
    Let mem_off be proc dict_str with mem_op0, "offset"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory offset is '8'", mem_off, "8"
    Let mem_base be proc dict_str with mem_op0, "base"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "memory base is 'rsp'", mem_base, "rsp"

    Note: --- instr[5] call foo : identifier operand ---
    Let call_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 5
    Let call_mn be proc dict_str with call_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[5] mnemonic is 'call'", call_mn, "call"
    Let call_ops be proc instr_operands with call_instr
    Let call_op0 be proc list_at with call_ops, 0
    Let call_op0_type be proc dict_str with call_op0, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "call operand type is identifier", call_op0_type, "identifier"
    Let call_op0_name be proc dict_str with call_op0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "call target is 'foo'", call_op0_name, "foo"

    Note: --- instr[6] ret : no operands ---
    Let ret_instr be proc list_at with instrs1, 6
    Let ret_mn be proc dict_str with ret_instr, "mnemonic"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instr[6] mnemonic is 'ret'", ret_mn, "ret"
    Let ret_ops be proc instr_operands with ret_instr
    Let ret_opc be proc list_count with ret_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "ret has 0 operands", ret_opc, 0

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> assembly text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_x86_from_hir from X86Backend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced assembly text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted assembly is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted text -> HIR (the SECOND emission),
    Note: then assert the section streams are structurally equal. This is the
    Note: load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc x86_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted assembly produced HIR", hir2

    Let instrs2 be proc section_list with hir2, "instructions"
    Let instr_count2 be proc list_count with instrs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed preserves 7 instructions", instr_count2, 7

    Let dirs2 be proc section_list with hir2, "directives"
    Let labels2 be proc section_list with hir2, "labels"

    Note: Spot-check survival on the SECOND emission directly (not just stage 1).
    Let r_mem_instr be proc list_at with instrs2, 2
    Let r_mem_ops be proc instr_operands with r_mem_instr
    Let r_mem_op0 be proc list_at with r_mem_ops, 0
    Let r_mem_base be proc dict_str with r_mem_op0, "base"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip memory base survives", r_mem_base, "rsp"

    Let r_call_instr be proc list_at with instrs2, 5
    Let r_call_ops be proc instr_operands with r_call_instr
    Let r_call_op0 be proc list_at with r_call_ops, 0
    Let r_call_name be proc dict_str with r_call_op0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip call target survives", r_call_name, "foo"

    Let r_label be proc list_at with labels2, 0
    Let r_label_name be proc dict_str with r_label, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip label name survives", r_label_name, "main"

    Note: --- Full structural equality across all three sections ---
    Let instrs_equal be proc instr_streams_equal with instrs1, instrs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip instructions structurally equal", instrs_equal, 1

    Let dirs_equal be proc named_streams_equal with dirs1, dirs2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip directives structurally equal", dirs_equal, 1

    Let labels_equal be proc named_streams_equal with labels1, labels2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip labels structurally equal", labels_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
